name: Alex Gladstein üåã ‚ö°
tweet: 27/  ...and 1.6 billion suffer under double- or triple-digit inflation, but in the West, too.  Even the most hardened skeptics are admitting that yes, Bitcoin has a use case, somewhere.  But why?

name: Alex Gladstein üåã ‚ö°
tweet: 26/ Already as you read this there are tens of millions of people around the world who are peacefully opting into Bitcoin.  Not just in dictatorships and broken economies, where 4.3 billion languish under authoritarians...

name: Alex Gladstein üåã ‚ö°
tweet: 25/ This isn‚Äôt simply about how money and finance works ‚Äî though you‚Äôll learn a lot about that along the way ‚Äî it‚Äôs a book about how we can, and how we must, harness the power of Bitcoin to secure liberty in the electronic age.

name: Alex Gladstein üåã ‚ö°
tweet: 22/ In the book‚Äôs crescendo, chapter six, ‚ÄúBitcoin Is Venice,‚Äù we get a clarion call for a better future: more inclusive, less exploitative, filled with choice and reason and compassion.

name: Alex Gladstein üåã ‚ö°
tweet: 21/ These lucid and lively pages explore all the nooks and crannies of the impact Bitcoin will leave on the world, especially in regard to investing, communications, culture, energy use, environmental sustainability, and how we build our communities.

name: Alex Gladstein üåã ‚ö°
tweet: 16/ Whereas those achieved change through new hierarchical structures, Bitcoin will change the world through decentralization.  As more and more people begin to realize that Bitcoin is monetizing right in front of our eyes, creating an alternative...

name: Alex Gladstein üåã ‚ö°
tweet: 13/ Bitcoin fixes this and helps us escape but not by violence.  It is ‚Äúnot a sword for Theseus to fight the Minotaur, but a thread to follow to exit the Labyrinth.‚Äù  And exit we shall.  We, after all, owe the Minotaur nothing.  Let the beast starve.  We‚Äôll find our own way out.

name: Alex Gladstein üåã ‚ö°
tweet: 10/ But against the facts, Bitcoin users are still routinely told by authorities that their choice ‚Äî opting peacefully into a new, fair, and neutral monetary system ‚Äî is wrong, immoral, or even treasonous.

name: Alex Gladstein üåã ‚ö°
tweet: 9/ That Bitcoin is for criminals. That it‚Äôs a Ponzi scheme. That it‚Äôs destroying the planet.  Time, however, has shown that it has been dangerous and risky to not hold bitcoin, which has been, since inception, the best-performing financial asset in the world.

name: Alex Gladstein üåã ‚ö°
tweet: 8/ This book is a stunning rejection of this emerging neo-feudalism and its administrators.  Over the past decade, governments, economists, and journalists have relentlessly hammered into the minds of their populations and audiences that Bitcoin is dangerous and risky.

name: Alex Gladstein üåã ‚ö°
tweet: 6/ ...today the Bitcoin network is the path to escaping the broken and unsustainable post-1971 political economy.  In newspapers and on television we are told not to worry about inflation, that employment is more important than saving, and that we can own nothing and be happy.

name: Alex Gladstein üåã ‚ö°
tweet: 3/ ... and foretell why and how things would change in the coming decades?  What you have in your hands, dear reader, is a book that will do just this for you today, as we approach the Bitcoin Renaissance.
